      "code_changes": [
        {
          "content": "{\n  \"buggy_files\": [\n    \"sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c\"\n  ],\n  \"buggy_functions\": [\n    \"azx_resume\",\n    \"azx_rirb_get_response\"\n  ],\n  \"confidence\": 0.95,\n  \"reasoning\": \"After analyzing the HDA Intel sound regression bug (works in v3.6.11, broken in v3.7.1+), the root cause is that the chip->polling_mode and chip->single_cmd flags are set to 1 during timeout handling in azx_rirb_get_response() (lines 912 and 951) but are never reset during suspend/resume cycles. This causes the following issue: (1) During normal operation, if a codec communication timeout occurs, azx_rirb_get_response() sets chip->single_cmd=1 as a fallback mode. (2) When the system suspends, azx_suspend() calls azx_stop_chip() which sets chip->initialized=0, but leaves chip->single_cmd=1 and chip->polling_mode unchanged. (3) When the system resumes, azx_resume() calls azx_init_chip(). However, azx_init_chip() has a check 'if (!chip->single_cmd)' (line 1222) before calling azx_init_cmd_io(). Since chip->single_cmd is still 1, the CORB/RIRB command I/O is never reinitialized. (4) Furthermore, azx_reset() also checks 'if (!chip->single_cmd)' (line 1105) before enabling unsolicited responses. With chip->single_cmd=1, unsolicited responses are not enabled. (5) The chip is now stuck in degraded single_cmd mode after resume, causing unreliable codec communication, timeouts, and the reported 'choppy sound' with 2-second silences. The fix is to reset chip->polling_mode and chip->single_cmd to 0 in azx_resume() before calling azx_init_chip(), allowing the chip to reinitialize in normal RIRB mode after waking from suspend.\"\n}\n",
          "file_path": "/workspace/fault_localization_result.json",
          "sequence": 69,
          "type": "write"
        }
