          "subtype": "message",
          "text": "Perfect! I've completed the fault localization analysis for the HDA Intel sound regression bug. Here's a summary of my findings:\n\n## Fault Localization Summary\n\n**Buggy File**: `sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c`\n\n**Buggy Functions**: \n- `azx_resume()` - Missing flag reset during resume\n- `azx_rirb_get_response()` - Sets persistent flags that cause degraded mode\n\n**Confidence**: 0.95\n\n### Root Cause Analysis:\n\nThe bug occurs because communication timeout fallback flags (`chip->polling_mode` and `chip->single_cmd`) are set during codec communication errors but are **never reset** during suspend/resume cycles.\n\n**The Problem Flow**:\n1. During normal operation, if a codec communication timeout occurs in `azx_rirb_get_response()`, the driver sets `chip->single_cmd=1` as a fallback (line 951)\n2. When the system suspends, `azx_suspend()` \u2192 `azx_stop_chip()` sets `chip->initialized=0`, but **leaves** `chip->single_cmd=1`\n3. When the system resumes, `azx_resume()` calls `azx_init_chip()`, but due to the persistent `chip->single_cmd=1`:\n   - Line 1222: `if (!chip->single_cmd)` prevents CORB/RIRB from being reinitialized\n   - Line 1105: `if (!chip->single_cmd)` prevents unsolicited responses from being enabled\n4. The chip stays in degraded `single_cmd` mode, causing unreliable communication\n5. This results in timeouts and the reported \"choppy sound\" with 2-second silences\n\n**Why This is a Regression**: In v3.6.11, the suspend/resume code likely properly reset these fallback flags, but this was broken in v3.7.1.\n\n**The Fix**: Reset `chip->polling_mode` and `chip->single_cmd` to 0 in `azx_resume()` before calling `azx_init_chip()`, allowing the chip to reinitialize in normal RIRB mode after waking from suspend.\n\nThe fault localization result has been written to `/workspace/fault_localization_result.json`.",
